Description:en: Antibiotic (IV, topical) used for gram-negative infections.
Drugs used to prevent and treat infections from microorganisms
Sulfa drug-pyrimethamine combinations are highly active blood schizonticides against P. falciparum but are less effective against other Plasmodium species.
Drug used for pain relief, fever, and antiplatelet actions.
A crystalline compound C8H9NO2 that is a hydroxy derivative of acetanilide and is used in chemical synthesis and in medicine instead of aspirin to relieve pain and fever.
Antibiotic most often used for urinary tract infections.
Antiparasitic agent most often used for leprosy, malaria, and pneumocystis carinii pneumonia infections.
Topical antiseptic used to sterilize skin for invasive procedures.
A broad-spectrum tetracycline antibiotic C22H24N2O8 with potent antibacterial activity that is often taken by travelers as a prophylactic against diarrhea.
Antibiotic used in malaria prophylaxis and treatment.
Antibiotic used in malaria prophylaxis and treatment.
Antibiotic used in malaria prophylaxis and treatment.
A synthetic compound with a strong diuretic action, used especially in the treatment of oedema.Diuretic that works mainly upon the loop of Henle.
Antibiotic (IV, topical) used for gram-negative infections.
Tinidazole is an anti-parasitic drug widely used throughout Europe and the Third World as treatment for a variety of amebic and parasitic infections.

Metronidazole is an antibiotic especially effective against anaerobic infections.  In addition, it has anti-inflammatory properties in the large intestine and is a very effective anti-diarrhea medication.  It is an effective antibiotic against certain protozoal infections, especially Giardia.

A barbiturate used to control epilepsy and as a sedative to relieve anxiety. It is also used for short-term treatment of insomnia. Anticonvulsant, recommended by the WHO as a first-line drug for partial and generalized tonic-clonic seizures.
A compound C20H22ClN3O derived from quinoline and used in the form of its dihydrochloride as an antimalarial.
A salt of quinine used as an antipyretic, antimalarial, antiperiodic, and bitter tonic. A natural white crystalline alkaloid having analgesic and anti-inflammatory properties.
A crystalline heterocyclic base C4H10N2 or C4H10N2·6H2O used especially as an anthelmintic.
A synthetic tranquilizer C16H13ClN2O used especially to relieve anxiety and tension and as a muscle relaxant.
A calcium channel blocker C17H18N2O6 that is a coronary vasodilator used especially in the treatment of angina pectoris.
Centrally acting alpha blocker, used as an antihypertensive drug C10H13NO4.
A beta-blocker C16H21NO2 used in the form of its hydrochloride in the treatment of hypertension, abnormal heart rhythms, heart failure and angina pectoris
An astringent iron salt obtained usually in pale green crystalline form FeSO4-7H2O and used in medicine chiefly for treating iron-deficiency anemia.

A crystalline vitamin C19H19N7O6 of the B complex that is required for normal production of red blood cells, that is used especially in the treatment of nutritional anemias, and that occurs especially in green leafy vegetables, liver, kidneys, dried beans, and mushrooms.

Oral hypoglycemic drug used to treat noninsulin-dependent diabetes, particularly in people whose diabetes cannot be controlled by diet alone. Chlorpropamide lowers blood sugar by stimulating the pancreas to secrete insulin and helping the body to use insulin efficiently.  Sulfonyl urea class.
An NSAID C19H16ClNO4 with analgesic and antipyretic properties used especially to treat painful inflammatory conditions (as rheumatoid arthritis and osteoarthritis).
A semisynthetic penicillin C16H19N3O5S derived from ampicillin.
A broad-spectrum antibiotic C11H12Cl2N2O5 isolated from cultures of a soil actinomycete of the genus Streptomyces (S. venezuelae) or prepared synthetically.
An antibacterial agent C12H12N2O3 that is used especially in the treatment of genitourinary infections.

A penicillin C16H19N3O4S that is effective against gram-negative and gram-positive bacteria and is used in anhydrous forms, as the trihydrate, or as the sodium salt to treat various infections of the urinary, respiratory, and intestinal tracts.

A penicillin C16H19N3O4S that is effective against gram-negative and gram-positive bacteria and is used in anhydrous forms, as the trihydrate, or as the sodium salt to treat various infections of the urinary, respiratory, and intestinal tracts.
An antibiotic C18H34N2O6S obtained from an actinomycete of the genus Streptomyces (S. lincolnensis) and effective especially against gram-positive bacteria.

A broad-spectrum antibiotic C37H67NO13 produced by a bacterium of the genus Streptomyces (S. erythreus), resembling penicillin in antibacterial activity, and effective also against amebas, treponemata, and pinworms.
A crystalline anticonvulsant compound C15H12N2O2 used in the form of its sodium salt in the treatment of epilepsy.
A suspension of insulin for injection in a buffered solution containing zinc chloride in which forms of insulin which are relatively slowly and rapidly absorbed are in the approximate ratio of 3:7.
reduced hyperglycemia, by injection, short acting
A suspension of insulin for injection to supplement naturally produced insulin.  Acts within 1 to 3 hours of injection.
An ointment that contains benzoic acid and salicylic acid and is used for its keratolytic effect in treating fungal skin diseases (as ringworm).
adrenal hormone used for inflammatory or allergic states or Addisonian crisis
An unstable compound H2O2 used especially as an oxidizing and bleaching agent and as an antiseptic.
Antacid used to relieve acid indigestion and heartburn.
topical antifungal to treat skin infections
topical antifungal agent to treat skin infections
Topical solution often used as an antifungal.
Drug used in the treatment of malaria.
A fluoroquinolone C16H18FN3O3 used topically to treat conjunctivitis and orally to treat various bacterial infections (as of the urinary tract).
Used for electrolyte deplection and dehydration.
Drug commonly used for scabies and head lice.

A synthetic antidiarrheal agent C29H33ClN2O2 that slows intestinal peristalsis and is administered in the form of its hydrochloride to control acute nonspecific diarrhea or chronic diarrhea associated with inflammatory bowel disease or to reduce fecal volume discharged from ileostomies.
Works by relaxing the involuntary muscle found in the walls of the stomach and intestines (gastrointestinal tract) and the genital organs and urinary tract (genitourinary tract).
A nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug used in the form of its sodium salt C14H10Cl2NNaO especially to treat the symptoms of rheumatoid arthritis, osteoarthritis, and ankylosing spondylitis.

An antibiotic organic base C21H39N7O12 that is produced by a soil actinomycete of the genus Streptomyces (S. griseus), is active against bacteria, and is used especially in the treatment of infections (as tuberculosis) by gram-negative bacteria.
Any of several white gelatinous or crystalline hydrates Al2O3·nH2O of alumina ; especially : one Al2O3·3H2O or Al(OH)3 used in medicine as an antacid.
A penicillinase-resistant, semisynthetic penicillin which has been used primarily in the treatment of infections due to benzylpenicillin-resistant staphylococci.
A preparation of amoxicillin and the potassium salt of clavulanic acid to provide beta-lactam resistance.
Vitamin preparation containing several Vitamin types.

A glucocorticoid C21H26O5 that is a dehydrogenated analog of cortisone and is used as an anti-inflammatory agent especially in the treatment of arthritis, as an antineoplastic agent, and as an immunosuppressant.
Antidote to a poisonous snake bite.
A mixture of zinc oxide or zinc carbonate with a small amount of ferric oxide that is used in lotions, liniments, and ointments.  Often used to prevent itching.
A semisynthetic cephalosporin antibiotic C18H18N8O7S3 that is administered parenterally in the form of its sodium salt.
A synthetic antiretroviral nucleoside (C10H12N2O4) that is an analog of thymidine and is administered orally in the treatment of HIV infection.
An antiviral drug (C8H11N3O3S) that is a synthetic nucleoside analog acting against HIV by inhibiting reverse transcriptase.
A non-nucleoside analogue that is used as an antiviral drug in the treatment of HIV infection.
A non-nucleoside drug used to treat HIV infection.
A protease-inhibiting drug usually used in combination with other drugs to suppress the replication of HIV.
A crystalline antibacterial compound (C6H7N3O) used in the treatment of tuberculosis.
An ACE inhibitor administered orally in the form of its hydrochloride C25H30N2O5-HCl to treat hypertension.
A cyclic nucleoside C8H11N5O3 used especially to treat the symptoms of the genital form of herpes simplex.
A benzodiazepine tranquilizer C17H13ClN4 used especially in the treatment of mild to moderate anxiety.
A semisynthetic macrolide antibiotic C38H72N2O12 that is derived from erythromycin and is used especially as an antibacterial agent.
A semisynthetic cephalosporin antibiotic C16H16N4O8S that is administered parenterally usually in the form of its sodium salt or an ester derivative.
A fluoroquinolone C17H18FN3O3 that is often administered in the form of its hydrochloride and is effective especially against gram-negative bacteria.
Anti-mycobaterial drug used to treat active tuberculosis.  Always used with other antimycobacterial agents.
Fluconazole is an antifungal medication of the azole (triazole) class, and is used to treat systemic yeast and fungal infections.  Commonly called Diflucan.
A tricyclic antidepressant drug C19H24N2 administered especially in the form of its hydrochloride.

An antiviral protease inhibitor C36H47N5O4 that by inhibiting the protease of HIV causes it to produce only immature noninfectious particles and that is used in the form of its sulfate in combination therapy with antiretroviral drugs (as AZT and lamivudine) to treat HIV infection.
An antiemetic drug C14H22ClN3O2 administered in the form of its hydrochloride.
Belongs to a group of drugs called proton pump inhibitors (PPI), inhibits gastric acid secretion.
Antibiotic that stops multiplication of bacteria by preventing the reproduction and repair of their genetic material. It is in a class of antibiotics called fluoroquinolones.
Proton pump inhibitor used to treat gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD).

A glucocorticoid C21H28O5 that is a dehydrogenated analog of hydrocortisone and is used often in the form of an ester or methyl derivative especially as an anti-inflammatory drug in the treatment of arthritis.
A crystalline phenolic alcohol C8H11NO3 of the vitamin B6 group found especially in cereals and convertible in the body into pyridoxal and pyridoxamine.
Semisynthetic antibiotic often used in tuberculosis, leprosy and meningococcal treatment/prophylaxis.  Also commonly known as Rifampin.
Combination drug also known as Rifater.  Used in the early treatment of tuberculosis.
Combination ferrous sulfate and folic acid supplement.
An H1 antagonist C21H25ClN2O3 administered orally in the form of its hydrochloride to treat allergic rhinitis and chronic urticaria.
Vaccination given for diphtheria, tetanus, and acellular pertussis infections

A mixture of relatively nontoxic antibiotic acids produced especially by molds of the genus Penicillium (as P. notatum or P. chrysogenum) and having a powerful bacteriostatic effect against various bacteria.
A potent glucocorticoid C22H29FO5 that is isomeric with dexamethasone and has potent anti-inflammatory activity.
Medication in a category of HIV antiretrovirals called reverse transcriptase inhibitors. Emtricitabine inhibits the reproduction of HIV in the body.
Combination of two medications in a category of HIV antriretrovirals called protease inhibitors. Lopinavir and ritonavir prevent HIV from multiplying.
An antiviral protease inhibitor C37H48N6O5S2 administered orally to treat HIV infection and AIDS.
A nucleoside analogue antiviral drug that inhibits replication of retroviruses such as HIV by interfering with the enzyme reverse transcriptase.
A nucleoside analogue antiviral drug that inhibits the replication of retroviruses such as HIV by interfering with the enzyme reverse transcriptase.
Beta2-adrenergic agonist used for asthma or reactive airways.
An antimalarial drug C26H30Cl2F3NO used in the form of its hydrochloride especially against chloroquine-resistant falciparum malaria.

Belongs to a class of drugs called Nucleotide Reverse Transcriptase Inhibitors (NtRTI).  The body converts these meds into a chemical that prevents HIV from reproducing in uninfected cells, but it does not help cells that have already been infected with the virus.
Medication in a category of HIV antiretrovirals called protease inhibitors. Amprenavir prevents HIV from maturing. This reduces the amount of infectious or active virus in your body.
A nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor (NRTI) that prevents HIV from altering the genetic material of healthy T-cells.
Deactivated tuberculous agent as basis for tuberculosis vaccination.

A synthetic steroid progestational hormone C24H34O4 that is used especially in the treatment of amenorrhea and abnormal uterine bleeding, in conjunction with conjugated estrogens to relieve the symptoms of menopause and to prevent osteoporosis, and as an injectable contraceptive.

A nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug C13H18O2 used in over-the-counter preparations to relieve pain and fever and in prescription strength especially to relieve the symptoms of rheumatoid arthritis and degenerative arthritis.
An antihistamine C16H19ClN2 that is usually administered in the form of its maleate.
A drug, C17H19ClN2S, derived from phenothiazine and used to suppress vomiting and as a sedative and a tranquilizer, especially in the treatment of schizophrenia and other psychotic states.
Drug is used to treat Parkinson's disease.
Combination antibiotic therapy.  First-line treatment for pneumocystis carinii pneumonia.
An antifungal agent administered especially in the form of its nitrate C18H14Cl4N2O-HNO3.
An antibiotic that is derived from a soil actinomycete of the genus Streptomyces (S. noursei) and is used especially in the treatment of candidiasis.
Carbamazepine (CBZ) is an anticonvulsant and mood stabilizing drug used primarily in the treatment of epilepsy and bipolar disorder, as well as trigeminal neuralgia.
An antihistamine C17H21NO used especially in the form of its hydrochloride to treat allergy symptoms and motion sickness.
A semisynthetic oral penicillin C19H17ClN3NaO5S effective especially against staphylococci which secrete beta-lactamase.
An antihistamine C13H22N4O3S that is administered in the form of its hydrochloride to inhibit gastric acid secretion.
A synthetic broad-spectrum antifungal agent C26H28Cl2N4O4 used to treat chronic internal and cutaneous disorders.
A phenothiazine tranquilizer C22H26F3N3OS used especially combined as a salt or ester.
A theophylline derivative C16H24N10O4 used especially to stimulate the heart in congestive heart failure and to dilate the air passages in respiratory disorders.
An antihypertensive drug C8H8N4 used in the form of its hydrochloride and acting to produce peripheral arteriolar dilation by relaxing vascular smooth muscle.
A tricyclic antidepressant drug C20H23N that is administered in the form of its hydrochloride salt and has been used to treat migraine headaches and neuropathic pain as well as depression.
An anthelmintic drug C11H12N2S administered in the form of its hydrochloride that also possesses immunostimulant properties and is used especially in the treatment of colon cancer.
A sulfa derivative topical antibacterial used primarily as a topical burn cream on second- and third-degree burns.

A broad-spectrum antibiotic C23H45N5O14 that is obtained from a bacterium of the genus Streptomyces (S. rimosus paromomycinus) and is used against intestinal amebiasis especially in the form of its sulfate.
Oral drug used to treat a variety of worm infections. It is related to mebendazole.

A drug C13H19NO4S that acts on renal tubular function and is used to increase the concentration of some drugs (as penicillin) in the blood by inhibiting their excretion and to increase the excretion of urates in gout.

A glucocorticoid drug C21H27FO6 that is administered especially in the form of its acetal and acetate derivatives for its anti-inflammatory and immunosuppressant effects and that is used chiefly in the treatment of skin disorders, asthma, and allergic rhinitis.
An agent (as an alkali or absorbent) that counteracts or neutralizes acidity.
A COX-2 blocker C17H14F3N3O2S that is administered orally especially to relieve the pain and inflammation of osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis.
A long-acting tricyclic antihistamine C22H23ClN2O2 used especially to relieve the symptoms of seasonal allergic rhinitis.

A precursor C14H19N5O4 of the antiviral agent penciclovir that after oral administration is converted to penciclovir by cellular kinases and that is used to treat especially shingles and herpes genitalis.
Medicine that increases the movements or contractions of the stomach and bowel. Domperidone is also used to treat nausea and vomiting caused by other drugs used to treat Parkinson's Disease.
An antifungal agent C22H17ClN2 used to treat candida infections, tinea, and ringworm.

Used to treat gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD), a condition in which backward flow of acid from the stomach causes heartburn and injury of the esophagus (food pipe between the mouth and stomach).
A triazole antifungal agent C35H38Cl2N8O4 used orally especially to treat blastomycosis and histoplasmosis.
A semisynthetic cephalosporin antibiotic C16H15N5O7S2 that is administered orally and is effective especially against gram-negative bacteria and streptococci.
A COX-2 inhibitor C17H14O4S used to relieve the signs and symptoms of osteoarthritis, to manage acute pain in adults, and to treat some forms of dysmenorrhea.
Combination drug used to treat tuberculosis, often used with other drugs.  It's also known as Ethizide.

ACE Inhibitor. Captopril is used to treat high blood pressure (hypertension), congestive heart failure, kidney problems caused by diabetes, and to improve survival after a heart attack
Lisinopril is in a group of drugs called ACE inhibitors. Lisinopril is used to treat high blood pressure, congestive heart failure, and to improve survival after a heart attack
Aldactone is a potassium sparing diuretic that prevents your body from absorbing too much salt and keeps your potassium levels from getting too low.
Carvedilol is a non selective beta blocker indicated in the treatment of mild to moderate congestive heart failure.

Atenolol is used alone or in combination with other medications to treat high blood pressure. It also is used to prevent angina (chest pain) and treat heart attacks. Atenolol is in a class of medications called beta blockers.
Amlodipine (as besylate, mesylate or maleate) is a long-acting calcium channel blocker (dihydropyridine) used as an anti-hypertensive and in the treatment of angina

Warfarin is used to prevent blood clots from forming or growing larger in your blood and blood vessels.

Digoxin helps the heart to beat more strongly and regularly. Digoxin is used to treat conditions such as congestive heart failure, atrial fibrillation, and atrial flutter.

A chemotherapeutic drug used to treat various conditions including Kaposi's sarcoma and lymphoma
Anti-fungal medication for animals and humans for the treatment of ringworm infections of skin and nails.
A carbonic anhydrase inhibitor that is used to treat glaucoma, epileptic seizures, benign intracranial hypertension (pseudotumor cerebri), altitude sickness, cystinuria, and dural ectasia.

A hormone and neurotransmitter, used as a drug to treat cardiac arrest and other cardiac dysrhythmias resulting in diminished or absent cardiac output, anaphylaxis, sepsis and as a bronchodilator for asthma.

Compound of atropine, a tropane alkaloid extracted from deadly plants of the family Solanceae.  A competitive antagonist for the muscarinic acetylcholine receptor, it serves as a drug with a wide variety of effects.
A form of penicillin, slowly absorbed into the circulation after intramuscular injection.  Useful when prolonged low concentrations of benzylpenicillin are required and appropriate.
A mineral supplement and the form of calcium most widely used in the treatment of hypocalcemia.
A topical steroid, used to treat many inflammatory and autoimmune conditions, e.g., rheumatoid arthritis.
A hormone that increases blood pressure and blood sugar, and reduces immune responses.
A common local anesthetic and antiarrhythmic drug. Lidocaine is used topically to relieve itching, burning and pain from skin inflammations, injected as a dental anesthetic, and in minor surgery
A stimulant laxative drug. It is typically prescribed for relief of constipation and for the management of neurogenic bowel dysfunction.

A lincosamide antibiotic. It is usually used to treat infections with anaerobic bacteria but can also be used to treat some protozoal diseases, such as malaria. It is a common topical treatment for acne, and can be useful against some methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) infections.
Compound used for hormone replacement therapy, typically in menopausal women.
An antidepressant of the selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) class.
An anti-diabetic drug in a class of medications known as sulfonylureas.

A typical antipsychotic. It is in the butyrophenone class of antipsychotic medications and has pharmacological effects similar to the phenothiazines.  Haloperidol is a primitive antipsychotic used in the treatment of schizophrenia and, more acutely, in the treatment of acute psychotic states and delirium.
A broad-spectrum antiparasitic medication, traditionally used against worms (except tapeworms), also found to be effective against most mites and some lice too.
The combination of carbidopa and levodopa is used to treat Parkinson's disease and Dopa-Responsive Dystonia (DRD).
A synthetic form of thyroxine (thyroid hormone).

A highly potent opiate analgesic drug.  Acts directly on the central nervous system (CNS) to relieve pain, and at synapses of the nucleus accumbens in particular. Morphine is highly addictive; tolerance, physical and psychological dependence develop rapidly.

A water-soluble vitamin, part of the vitamin B group.
An antibiotic. It is usually used in treating urinary tract infection.
A metal halide salt composed of potassium and chlorine.

A diuretic and is used as an antiandrogen.
A chemical compound that has found clinical use as an anticonvulsant and mood-stabilizing drug, primarily in the treatment of epilepsy, bipolar disorder, and less commonly major depression.
